{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15855"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15855"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.05,0.85,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8546"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48338"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1331"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45762"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of central chest discomfort. The pain occurs predictably when walking up hills or climbing stairs, and resolves within five minutes of rest. She denies any episodes at rest or nocturnal symptoms. She has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. She is an active smoker with a 30 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 148/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Heart sounds are normal with no added sounds. Chest is clear to auscultation. The ECG shows T wave flattening in leads V4-V6. High-sensitivity troponin T is 8 ng/L (0-14).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ST-elevation myocardial infarction","Unstable angina","Prinzmetal angina","Stable angina","Non-ST-elevation myocardial infarction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of stable angina. The key features supporting \u003Cstrong\u003Estable angina\u003C/strong\u003E include exertional symptoms occurring at predictable levels of activity, prompt resolution with rest, and absence of rest pain or crescendo pattern. The presence of cardiovascular risk factors (smoking, hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia) increases the pre-test probability of coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnstable angina\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by new onset symptoms, crescendo pattern (symptoms occurring with progressively less exertion), or rest pain. These features are not present in this case, where symptoms are predictable and stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EST-elevation myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E would show characteristic ST-segment elevation on ECG and typically presents with severe, prolonged pain not relieved by rest. The normal troponin and stable pattern of symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-ST-elevation myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E would show elevation in cardiac biomarkers, specifically troponin. While the ECG changes can be non-specific, the normal troponin and stable symptom pattern exclude this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrinzmetal angina\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs at rest in the early morning hours and is associated with transient ST elevation due to coronary artery spasm. The exertional pattern of symptoms and ECG changes do not fit with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of stable angina includes risk factor modification, antiplatelet therapy, and consideration of beta blockers or calcium channel blockers for symptom control. Exercise stress testing may be useful to confirm the diagnosis and assess functional capacity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stable angina typically occurs with predictable levels of exertion and is relieved by rest.","Risk factors including smoking, hypertension, and hypercholesterolaemia increase the likelihood of coronary artery disease.","Normal cardiac biomarkers and non-specific ECG changes are common in stable angina."],"references":["2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48338"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15855"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48338"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T08:47:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T08:48:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8546"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"